The Nigerian Shippers Council has called for collaboration with the Nigerian Customs Service in order to ensure an easier way of doing business at the Nigerian ports. Speaking when he paid a courtesy call to the Comptroller General of the Nigerian Customs (CGC) Service, the Nigerian Shippers Council executive secretary, Mr Hassan Bello said one of his purposes of the visit was to look at how the two agencies can collaborate to make cargo clearing faster and meet the eight days standard obtained Internationally. He also noted that in order to achieve this, there was a need for the deployment of scanners at the ports which would scan cargoes within minutes in line with international best practices and reduce the rigorous process of physical scanning of cargoes which has made it possible for Nigerian cargoes to spend 32 days at the ports Bello also called for the deployment of Inspectors to the Kaduna dry ports for assessments of goods to be exported, noting that Nigeria is now focussed on exporting goods even as they focus on importing goods too Other areas of collaborating collaboration, which the shippers council boss noted include reduction in double assessment of cargoes at the port which leads to the delay and the clearance While speaking, the CGC, Col. Hameed Ali (rtd) noted that the Nigerian Customs have advanced in technology, which would make cargo clearance faster. He noted that very soon, the Nigerian Customs will deploy a single window of e-customs, which will make every relevant stakeholders to cue into, thereby making the clearance of goods faster. He also urged the stakeholders in the shipping line to collaborate and develop a system that would help in cuing in into the e-customs when deployed. 